Problems

  1. Let \(X \sim \text{Normal}(200, 40)\) so \(\mu = 200\) and \(\sigma = 40\).
  • Find and display the values \(x_1\) and \(x_2\) such that:
    • \(x_1 < \mu < x_2\);
    • \(x_1\) and \(x_2\) are equidistant from \(\mu\) (\(\mu - x_1 = x_2 - \mu\));
    • The area under the density between \(x_1\) and \(x_2\) equals 0.8 (\(\mathsf{P}(x_1 < X < x_2) = 0.8\)).
  • Create a graph showing the normal density with the area between \(x_1\) and \(x_2\) being shaded.

Solution

mu = 200
sigma = 40

x_1 = qnorm(0.1, mu, sigma)
x_2 = qnorm(0.9, mu, sigma)

x_1
## [1] 148.7379
x_2
## [1] 251.2621
gnorm(mu, sigma) +
  geom_norm_fill(mu, sigma, a = x_1, b = x_2)

pnorm(x_2, mu, sigma) - pnorm(x_1, mu, sigma)
## [1] 0.8
  1. Create a small data frame with variables:

  • p equal to the values 0.9, 0.95, 0.975, 0.99, and 0.995;

  • x equal to the p quantile of the \(\text{Normal}(400, 20)\) distribution;

  • z equal to the z-score of x, \(z = (x - \mu)/\sigma\).

  • Print this full table.

  • If the values of \(\mu\) and \(\sigma\) were changed and you repeated the problem for the same values of p, which of the columns x and z would change and which would remain the same? Briefly explain.

[Type your response here.]

Solution

mu = 200
sigma = 40

prob2 = tibble(
  p = c(0.9, 0.95, 0.975, 0.99, 0.995),
  x = qnorm(p, mu, sigma),
  z = (x - mu) / sigma
)

prob2
## # A tibble: 5 × 3
##       p     x     z
##   <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 0.9    251.  1.28
## 2 0.95   266.  1.64
## 3 0.975  278.  1.96
## 4 0.99   293.  2.33
## 5 0.995  303.  2.58

The values of x would change, but the values of z would stay the same. The variable x is the location of quantiles in the units of the problem and change if \(\mu\) and \(\sigma\) change.

The variable z is the location of the quantiles in standard units and these are the same for all normal curves

  1. Suppose that \(X \sim \text{Normal}(200, 40)\).

  • What is \(\mathsf{P}(180 < X < 250)\)? Create a graph which lets you visualize this probability.

  • What is the 0.05 quantile of this distribution? Create a graph which lets you visualize this quantile.

Solution

## moments
mu = 200
sigma = 40
a = 180
b = 250

## probability
p3 = pnorm(b, mu, sigma) - pnorm(a, mu, sigma)
p3
## [1] 0.5858127
## graph
gnorm(mu, sigma) +
  geom_norm_fill(mu, sigma, a = a, b = b)

## quantile
q3 = qnorm(0.05, mu, sigma)
q3
## [1] 134.2059
gnorm(mu, sigma) +
  geom_norm_fill(mu, sigma, b = q3)

  1. Heights in a population of American adult males are approximately normal with a mean of 70 inches and a standard deviation of 3 inches.
  • What proportion of American adult males are taller than two meters tall? (One meter equals 39.37 inches.)
  • What is the 95th percentile of American adult male height?

Solution

mu = 70
sigma = 3

1 - pnorm(2*39.37, mu, sigma)
## [1] 0.001787963
qnorm(0.95, mu, sigma)
## [1] 74.93456

Only about 1.8% of American adult males are taller than two meters

The 95th percentile of height is about 74.9 inches tall, or nearly 6 foot 3 inches tall.

  1. The following code chunk graphs the probabilities of the \(\text{Binomial}(50, 0.37)\) distribution with bars of width one centered at the possible values of the random variable from the 0.001 to the 0.999 quantiles of the distribution. Bars at the 0.90 quantile and to the right are filled in a dark red color (“firebrick”) and other values have the bars filled in gray.
n = 50
p = 0.37

prob5_df = tibble(
  x = seq(qbinom(0.001, n, p), qbinom(0.999, n, p), 1),
  prob = dbinom(x, n, p)
)

plot5 = ggplot(prob5_df, aes(x = x, y = prob)) +
  geom_col(width = 1, color = "black", fill = "lightgray") +
  geom_col(width = 1, color = "black", fill = "firebrick",
           data = prob5_df %>% filter(x >= qbinom(0.90, n, p))) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0) +
  xlab("x") +
  ylab("Probability") +
  ggtitle("Binomial(50, 0.37) Distribution")

plot5

  • Create and display a small data frame with the following summary statistics of this distribution:

    • mu, equal to the mean;
    • sigma, equal to the standard deviation;
    • a_1, equal to the 0.90 quantile;
    • z_1, the z-score of a_1 (\(z = (x-\mu)/\sigma\));
    • a_2 equal to \(a_1 - 0.5\), the left endpoint of a bar of width 1 centered at a_1;
    • z_2, the z-score of a_2.

  • Modify the code to make the plot above by doing the following:

    • Only display the distribution for \(x \ge 20\).
    • Overlay a blue normal density where the mean and standard deviation match those of the binomial distribution
    • Fill in the area under the curve to the right of a_1 with a partly translucent color blue (settings fill = "blue", alpha=0.5) so that you see a violet color where this shading overlaps the firebrick red color of the exact binomial probabilities.

  • Make another plot by modifying from the previous problem, but fill the area to the right of a_2 instead of a_1.

  • Find:

    • the exact binomial probability \(\mathsf{P}(X \ge a_1)\) where \(a_1\) is the 0.90 quantile.
    • the area to the right of a_1 under the normal density
    • the area to the right of a_2 under the normal density

  • Briefly explain why one normal area is closer to the exact binomial calculation than the other, referring to your plots.

[Type your answer here]

Solution

n = 50
p = 0.37

prob5 = tibble(
  mu = n*p,
  sigma = sqrt(n*p*(1-p)),
  a_1 = qbinom(0.90, n, p),
  z_1 = (a_1 - mu) / sigma,
  a_2 = a_1 - 0.5,
  z_2 = (a_2 - mu) / sigma)

prob5
## # A tibble: 1 × 6
##      mu sigma   a_1   z_1   a_2   z_2
##   <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
## 1  18.5  3.41    23  1.32  22.5  1.17
mu = prob5$mu
sigma = prob5$sigma
a_1 = prob5$a_1
a_2 = prob5$a_2
a = 20

plot5b = prob5_df %>% 
  filter(x >= a) %>% 
ggplot(aes(x = x, y = prob)) +
  geom_col(width = 1, color = "black", fill = "lightgray") +
  geom_col(width = 1, color = "black", fill = "firebrick",
           data = prob5_df %>% filter(x >= qbinom(0.90, n, p))) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0) +
  xlab("x") +
  ylab("Probability") +
  ggtitle("Binomial(50, 0.37) Distribution",
          subtitle = "Right Tail") +
  geom_norm_density(mu, sigma, a = a)

plot5b +
  geom_norm_fill(mu, sigma, a = a_1, alpha = 0.5, fill = "blue")

plot5b +
  geom_norm_fill(mu, sigma, a = a_2, alpha = 0.5, fill = "blue")

## exact binomial
1 - pbinom(a_1 - 1, n, p)
## [1] 0.1213983
## normal approx 1
1 - pnorm(a_1, mu, sigma)
## [1] 0.09373102
## normal approx 2
1 - pnorm(a_2, mu, sigma)
## [1] 0.1206656

The second normal approximation is much closer to the true binomial distribution probability because of the correction for continuity.

  1. Suppose you are playing a coin flipping game with a friend, where you suspect the coin your friend provided is not a fair coin. In fact, you think the probability the coin lands heads is less than 0.5. To test this, you flip the coin 100 times and observe the coin lands heads 35 times.

  • If you assume the coin is fair (i.e., the probability of the coin landing heads is 0.5), what is the probability of observing 35 heads or fewer?

  • How small would \(p\) need to be (rounded to the nearest 0.01) for the probability of observing 35 or fewer heads to be at least 0.05?

  • Does it seem plausible that the coin is fair? Briefly explain.

Solution

n = 100
p = 0.5
x = 35

p6 = pbinom(35, 100, 0.5)
p6
## [1] 0.001758821
prob6 = tibble(p = seq(0.01, 0.5, 0.01),
               prob = pbinom(35, 100, p))

prob6 %>% 
  filter(prob > 0.05) %>% 
  slice_max(p)
## # A tibble: 1 × 2
##       p   prob
##   <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1  0.43 0.0639

If \(p = 0.5\), the probability of getting 35 or fewer heads is very small, about 0.0018, or less than 2 in 1000. It is more plausible that \(p\) is smaller than 0.5 where the probability of the observed outcome is much larger.

  1. Suppose that a random variable \(U\) is uniformly distributed between \(a = 100 - 10\sqrt{3} \doteq 82.679\) and \(b = 100 + 10\sqrt{3} \doteq 117.321\). For this distribution, \(\mathsf{E}(U) = 100\) and \(\mathsf{SD}(U) = 10\).

Here is a plot of the density function.

delta = 10*sqrt(3)
a = 100 - delta
b = 100 + delta

u_dist = tibble(
  u = c(a-1, a, a, b, b, b+1),
  f = c(0, 0, 1/(b-a), 1/(b-a), 0, 0)
)

ggplot(u_dist, aes(x = u, y = f)) +
  geom_line(color = "blue") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0)

This code chunk will generate four random variables \(U_1, \ldots, U_4\) from this uniform density, sort them, print the sample, and then print the mean, \(\overline{U}\).

## set the seed to keep the same values when reknitting
set.seed(2023)

u = runif(4, a, b) %>% sort()
u
## [1] 88.31966 94.29085 96.40149 98.84347
mean(u)
## [1] 94.46387

The next chunk of code will repeat this random sampling process \(B = 1,000,000\) times and save the sample means, using code form purrr.

B = 1000000
n = 4

delta = 10*sqrt(3)
a = 100 - delta
b = 100 + delta

prob7_df = tibble(
  u_bar = map_dbl(1:B, ~mean(runif(n, a, b))))

  • Find and display the sample mean and standard deviation (use sd()) of the the generated sample means from the previous simulation.

Solution

prob7 = prob7_df %>%

Solution

  • True probability from simulation

  summarize(prob = mean(between(u_bar, 96, 104))) %>% 
  pull(prob)

  • Estimate from normal curve

  • Graph

The normal estimate is a bit too large because the red normal density is larger than the blue estimated density between 96 and 104.

The worst-case scenario is about when \(a=4\) as these are the values where the density curves cross.
